The morphology characterized by TEM indicated that the N-CDs were quasi-spherical and uniformly dispersed without obvious agglomeration (Fig. 1
                        A). HRTEM image (the inset in Fig. 1A) displayed a well-resolved lattice morphology of N-CDs with a lattice spacing of 0.213 nm, corresponding to the diffraction plane (100) of graphene carbon. The particle sizes were relatively uniform with an average diameter size about 2.8 nm (Fig. 1B). XRD pattern revealed the crystallinity feature of N-CDs. The diffraction peak (002) located at 21.1° indicates the graphene structure of N-CDs (Fig. 1C) [21]. The functional groups of N-CDs as investigated with FT-IR showed that a strong peak centered at 3462 cm−1, which represents the stretching vibration of O-H and N-H. The peaks at 2957 cm−1, 1335 cm−1, and 844 cm−1 are attributed to the stretching and bending vibrations of C-H bond. The peaks at 1637 cm−1, 1572 cm−1, and 1441 cm−1 are ascribed to the stretching vibration of C = O, C = C, and C-N, respectively [31]. The peak at 1130 cm−1 represents the characteristic peak of C-O stretching vibration (Fig. 1D). The results of FT-IR proved that the synthesized N-CDs contain oxygen and nitrogen functional groups on the surface, such as -OH, -NH2, -COOH, which are involved in the excellent hydrophilicity of N-CDs [32]. A narrow size distribution of N-CDs with the height in the range of 1–3 nm and the average height about 2.5 nm is presented in the AFM images (Fig. 2
                        ). The results are consistent with the TEM results.
